  "prompt": "Do I need to freeze my allotment in sliding round of IPU?",
  "response": "In the context of admissions through the Indraprastha University (IPU) Common Entrance Test (CET), the process and requirements can vary from year to year. However, I can provide some general guidance on what usually happens in a sliding round:\n\n1. **Sliding Round**: This is typically a process where candidates who have already been allotted a seat in the previous rounds have a chance to get a seat in a higher preference course or college, depending on availability and their rank.\n\n2. **Freezing Your Allotment**: If you are satisfied with the seat allotted to you and do not wish to participate in further rounds, you will typically need to freeze your seat. This generally means accepting the allotted seat and paying the required fee to confirm your admission.\n\n3. **Not Freezing**: If you choose not to freeze your seat, you remain in the sliding process by default. This means your current seat is not confirmed, and you may be allotted a different seat in the sliding round based on availability and your preferences.\n\nIt's crucial to carefully read the official instructions provided by IPU for the specific admission year, as processes and rules can change. If you're at all unsure, I recommend contacting the IPU admissions office directly or visiting their official website for the most accurate and current information.",
